Determine impact of by-proxy cases

Regina H. Reynolds

UCL

24 September 2021

Aim: determine the impact of excluding by-proxy cases on AD-LBD and PD-LBD local \(r_g\)

1 Background

Both AD and PD GWASs used in this work include by-proxy cases, which are defined as individuals who have a parent with the disease. In AD, it has been shown that the genetic correlation with clinically diagnosed Alzheimer's disease is high (PMID: 29777097). However, mislabelling by-proxy cases when parents suffer from other types of dementia could lead to spurious genetic correlations. This is particularly relevant in comparisons of AD to LBD, which both present with cognitive decline. To assess the impact of by-proxy inclusions on local \(r_g\)'s with LBD, we used older releases of the AD and PD GWASs (AD2013 and PD2011) where by-proxy cases were not included.

2.3 Prepare input info file

phenotypes <- c("AD2013", "PD2011", "LBD2020") %>% sort()

gwas_details <- 
  readxl::read_xlsx(path = "/data/LDScore/GWAS/LDSC_GWAS_details.xlsx") %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    Original_name = Original_name %>% 
      stringr::str_replace_all("_", "\\.")
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::select(
    Original_name, 
    cases = N_case,
    controls = N_ctrl
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    # Rename AD to AD2013 to fit with LAVA file
    Original_name =
      case_when(Original_name == "AD" ~ "AD2013",
                TRUE ~ Original_name)
  )

input_info <- 
  tibble(
    phenotype = 
      list.files(
        path = gwas_dir,
        full.names = F,
        recursive = T,
        pattern = ".lava.gz"
      ) %>% 
      stringr::str_remove("/.*") %>% 
      stringr::str_replace_all("_", "\\."),
    filename = 
      list.files(
        path = gwas_dir,
        full.names = T,
        recursive = T,
        pattern = ".lava.gz"
      )
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    phenotype =
      case_when(phenotype == "AD" ~ "AD2013",
                TRUE ~ phenotype)
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(phenotype %in% phenotypes) %>% 
  dplyr::inner_join(
    gwas_details,
    by = c("phenotype" = "Original_name")
    ) %>% 
  dplyr::select(phenotype, cases, controls, filename)

write_delim(
  input_info,
  path = file.path(here::here("results", "05_noproxy_univar_bivar"),
                   "input.info.txt"),
  delim = "\t"
)

2.5 Loading results

Once run, results can be loaded using the following code chunk:

files <- 
  list.files(
  path = 
    here::here("results",
               "05_noproxy_univar_bivar"),
  pattern = ".lava.rds", 
  full.names = T
)

results <- 
  setNames(
    object = files %>% 
      lapply(., function(file){
        
        list <-
          file %>% 
          readRDS() 
        
        if(!is.null(list)){
          list %>%
            purrr::discard(is.null) %>%
            qdapTools::list_df2df() %>%
            dplyr::select(-X1)
        }

      }),
    nm = files %>% 
      basename() %>% 
      str_remove(".lava.rds") %>% 
      str_remove(".*:") %>% 
      str_remove(".*\\.")
  )
global <- 
  read_delim(
    file = here::here("results", "05_noproxy_univar_bivar", "ldsc_corr", "ldsc_correlations.txt"),
    delim = "\t"
    )

3 Methods

Methods are as described in 01_preparing_inputs_gwas.html. LD blocks were filtered to include only those where significant bivariate local \(r_g\)'s were observed between LBD and either by-proxy AD or PD GWASs. This limited the number of LD blocks to 1 (locus 2351). Bivariate local correlations were only performed for pairs of traits which both exhibited a significant univariate local genetic signal (p < 0.05/1, where the denominator represents the total number of tested loci). This resulted in a total of 1 bivariate test spanning 1 distinct loci.

combn <-
  global$p1 %>%
  unique() %>%
  combn(m = 2) %>%
  t() %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  dplyr::rename(
    p1 = V1,
    p2 = V2
  )

global_signif <- 
  global %>% 
  dplyr::filter(
    !p1==p2
  ) %>% 
  dplyr::inner_join(combn) %>%
  dplyr::filter(
    p < 0.05/nrow(combn)
  )

  DT::datatable(rownames = FALSE,
                options = list(scrollX = TRUE),
                class = 'white-space: nowrap')

  results$bivar %>%

4.2 Global correlations versus bivariate tests

4.2.1 Text

  • Global cross-trait correlations revealed a significant positive correlation between LBD and PD2011 (without by-proxy cases), as previously observed when using PD2019 (with by-proxy cases).
  • In univariate tests, a negative variance estimate was calculated for PD2011 in locus 2351 (likely due to insufficient signal), thus this trait was dropped from the analysis.
  • The bivariate test revealed a significant positive correlation between AD2013 (without by-proxy cases; rho = 0.79, p = \(8.00284\times 10^{-131}\)) and LBD, as previously observed using AD2019 (with by-proxy cases; rho = 0.63, p = \(1.24076\times 10^{-139}\)). This results suggests that the local \(r_g\) observed in locus 2351 between AD and LBD is not driven by the inclusion of by-proxy cases.

4.2.2 Figures

plot_global_corr(
  global_corr = global,
  n_phenotypes = 3
)

Figure 4.1: Global genetic correlations between pairs of phenotypes. Significant negative and positive correlations are indicated by blue and red fill, respectively. Non-significant correlations (p >= 0.05/n_tests) have a grey fill. 

plot_edge_diagram(
  bivar_corr = 
    bivar_bonf,
  phen = fct_disease,
  multiple_corr = FALSE,
  ncol = 3
)

Figure 4.2: Edge diagram for each locus showing the standardised coefficient for genetic correlation (rho) for each significant bivariate local genetic correlations (p < 0.05/n_tests). Significant negative and positive correlations are indicated by blue and red colour, respectively.
